1
00:00:09,667 --> 00:00:13,084
Hello, my name is Dr. Michael Foale.

2
00:00:13,117 --> 00:00:16,280
I'm a former NASA astronaut.

3
00:00:17,270 --> 00:00:21,603
I was born in Great Britain,
but my mother is American,

4
00:00:21,604 --> 00:00:24,100
and my father was
a British Royal Air Force pilot.

5
00:00:24,753 --> 00:00:27,642
With that combination, I was able to apply

6
00:00:27,643 --> 00:00:31,765
to the National Aeronautics
and Space Administration, NASA,

7
00:00:33,042 --> 00:00:34,700
to become an astronaut.

8
00:00:35,451 --> 00:00:38,010
It began with many small steps

9
00:00:38,510 --> 00:00:43,013
and the first of them was to finish
a PhD in Astrophysics

10
00:00:43,014 --> 00:00:45,301
at Cambridge University in England,

11
00:00:45,681 --> 00:00:51,482
to move across to the Houston
Johnson Space Center in America,

12
00:00:51,803 --> 00:00:54,573
and while wanting to be an astronaut,

13
00:00:54,574 --> 00:00:59,457
I was not yet able to apply
because there wasn't a selection process.

14
00:00:59,458 --> 00:01:00,793
I had to find a job.

15
00:01:02,758 --> 00:01:06,241
I worked in Houston
at the Johnson Space Center

16
00:01:06,955 --> 00:01:13,723
for two years before I was finally
selected as an astronaut.

17
00:01:25,989 --> 00:01:27,461
When I was working at NASA,

18
00:01:28,271 --> 00:01:32,620
I had a job in payload operations.

19
00:01:32,621 --> 00:01:37,526
This was a job very much
like the ones you've seen

20
00:01:37,527 --> 00:01:39,394
at the European Space Agency

21
00:01:39,395 --> 00:01:41,804
where people are working
in a control center,

22
00:01:41,805 --> 00:01:46,944
they have knowledge about the spacecraft
that they are controlling and monitoring

23
00:01:46,945 --> 00:01:50,369
as they carry out their missions in space,

24
00:01:50,370 --> 00:01:56,775
and my job was to carry out
payload operations for the Space Shuttle.

25
00:01:57,818 --> 00:02:02,070
The Space Shuttle
carried cargo into space,

26
00:02:02,071 --> 00:02:06,635
including telecommunication satellites
that we all take for granted today,

27
00:02:06,636 --> 00:02:10,437
that achieve all
of the amazing communications

28
00:02:10,439 --> 00:02:13,111
that we have around the Earth
and between the planets.

29
00:02:13,112 --> 00:02:16,486
These satellites were being carried
on the Space Shuttle.

30
00:02:16,487 --> 00:02:22,951
My job was to know how
the satellite worked, functionally,

31
00:02:22,952 --> 00:02:24,727
not in terms of the electronics

32
00:02:24,728 --> 00:02:26,820
and all of the details
of the mechanical engineering,

33
00:02:26,821 --> 00:02:30,295
but functionally: what key operations
take place in that satellite,

34
00:02:30,296 --> 00:02:32,737
and to monitor the behavior
of that satellite

35
00:02:32,738 --> 00:02:34,748
when it was launched on the Space Shuttle.

36
00:02:35,920 --> 00:02:42,204
I could tell you now a little bit
about what I was doing

37
00:02:42,205 --> 00:02:43,978
during those missions.

38
00:02:46,058 --> 00:02:50,945
In the control center
I was called the "Payload Officer"

39
00:02:50,946 --> 00:02:54,040
and I was sitting
in the mission control center

40
00:02:54,041 --> 00:02:57,227
that I think many people
in the world have seen on TV

41
00:02:57,228 --> 00:02:59,360
when we've conducted space missions,

42
00:02:59,537 --> 00:03:01,451
both to the International Space Station,

43
00:03:01,571 --> 00:03:04,411
but before that, Space Shuttle missions,

44
00:03:04,412 --> 00:03:08,382
and before that, the Apollo missions
that landed on the Moon.

45
00:03:08,933 --> 00:03:10,238
In that control center

46
00:03:10,239 --> 00:03:13,254
-- which was an amazing honor
for me, to do that as a young man.

47
00:03:13,374 --> 00:03:14,949
I was about 27.

48
00:03:16,544 --> 00:03:19,851
I had a sign in front of me
called "Payload Officer"

49
00:03:20,614 --> 00:03:24,236
and when the Space Shuttle, for example,

50
00:03:25,626 --> 00:03:30,293
Space Transportation System,
STS-61B launched,

51
00:03:31,375 --> 00:03:36,695
we were launching
two Satcom RCA satellites

52
00:03:36,696 --> 00:03:38,566
to geosynchronous orbit.

53
00:03:39,918 --> 00:03:45,456
Those satellites were probably
worth 200 or 300 million dollars each

54
00:03:45,457 --> 00:03:47,371
but they were flying
on the Space Shuttle

55
00:03:47,491 --> 00:03:49,413
for quite a low price,

56
00:03:49,414 --> 00:03:52,273
much lower than the price
of building those satellites.

57
00:03:53,216 --> 00:03:56,657
I had, in the previous year,
visited that company,

58
00:03:56,658 --> 00:03:59,936
worked with their engineers,
worked with their program manager,

59
00:03:59,937 --> 00:04:02,092
and developed drawings and procedures

60
00:04:02,093 --> 00:04:06,150
that the astronauts
that were launching on STS-61B

61
00:04:06,151 --> 00:04:11,173
would use to deploy that satellite
out of the cargo bay of the Space Shuttle

62
00:04:11,174 --> 00:04:16,485
where the Shuttle
would then move away from it,

63
00:04:16,486 --> 00:04:21,279
and it would fire its final rocket motor,
a solid rocket motor,

64
00:04:21,279 --> 00:04:27,558
and thrust it out
towards geosynchronous orbit.

65
00:04:28,282 --> 00:04:30,543
All those tasks on those missions,

66
00:04:30,544 --> 00:04:35,470
the Space Shuttle missions
51G, 51I, 61B and 61C,

67
00:04:35,471 --> 00:04:40,015
they were all cargo missions
on the Space Shuttle

68
00:04:40,016 --> 00:04:44,284
carrying communications satellites
up to geosynchronous orbit.

69
00:04:44,285 --> 00:04:46,646
Now, the Space Shuttle
can't go up that high.

70
00:04:46,647 --> 00:04:48,691
You can only go to Low Earth Orbit.

71
00:04:48,692 --> 00:04:50,472
But my job was,

72
00:04:50,473 --> 00:04:52,850
as the payload officer
in the control center,

73
00:04:52,851 --> 00:04:55,760
to know the details of those satellites,
how they worked;

74
00:04:56,619 --> 00:05:00,747
and help train the astronauts
with procedures I wrote and developed,

75
00:05:00,748 --> 00:05:02,320
knowing the satellite,

76
00:05:02,321 --> 00:05:05,794
and then the astronaut trainers
would train the astronauts

77
00:05:05,795 --> 00:05:10,525
to operate those satellites
in a simulator,

78
00:05:10,526 --> 00:05:14,484
and then during the actual mission,
I would be in the mission control center

79
00:05:14,485 --> 00:05:19,764
watching displays, seeing
how those satellites' critical parameters

80
00:05:19,765 --> 00:05:21,994
are behaving on the Space Shuttle.

81
00:05:21,995 --> 00:05:25,108
At the right moment I would give the go

82
00:05:25,109 --> 00:05:27,786
to the flight director
in that control center

83
00:05:27,787 --> 00:05:31,355
to say "flight, we are go for deploy"

84
00:05:31,375 --> 00:05:36,028
at which point the CAPCOM
would call the crew on the Space Shuttle

85
00:05:36,029 --> 00:05:41,013
and say, "Columbia, we are go
for the deploy of the Satcom,"

86
00:05:41,014 --> 00:05:43,070
at which point they would throw a switch,

87
00:05:43,071 --> 00:05:47,003
and it would release locks
in the cargo bay of the Space Shuttle,

88
00:05:47,004 --> 00:05:50,221
and the satellite would rise up
out of the cargo bay

89
00:05:50,222 --> 00:05:54,724
with a booster underneath it,
a solid rocket booster.

90
00:05:54,725 --> 00:06:00,580
Then the Space Shuttle would move away
to a safe distance, a few kilometers,

91
00:06:00,581 --> 00:06:04,832
and about 45 minutes later,
after that deploy,

92
00:06:04,833 --> 00:06:09,215
as the satellite crosses
the right point in the orbit,

93
00:06:09,216 --> 00:06:14,874
actually intersects the plane
of the orbit with the Equator

94
00:06:14,875 --> 00:06:17,226
because they're going
into geosynchronous orbit,

95
00:06:17,227 --> 00:06:19,509
then that PAM motor would fire

96
00:06:19,510 --> 00:06:21,497
and the solid rocket motor would boost it

97
00:06:21,498 --> 00:06:27,722
and add another 3,000 meters per second

98
00:06:27,723 --> 00:06:31,577
to get the satellite
up to geosynchronous orbit.

99
00:06:31,578 --> 00:06:34,956
Once that motor's fired, my job's done

100
00:06:34,957 --> 00:06:37,624
and all the astronauts
on the Space Shuttle

101
00:06:37,625 --> 00:06:40,460
and flight controllers
in the mission control center room

102
00:06:40,461 --> 00:06:42,004
would all relax and cheer,

103
00:06:42,005 --> 00:06:43,297
because from that point on,

104
00:06:43,417 --> 00:06:47,105
all of the operations were
in the hands of the satellite builder

105
00:06:47,106 --> 00:06:49,478
and that's basically what I did

106
00:06:49,479 --> 00:06:53,274
for a year and a half
while working at NASA

107
00:06:53,275 --> 00:06:59,382
before I was finally selected
by the NASA astronaut selection committee

108
00:06:59,383 --> 00:07:02,102
which was on my third try, by the way.

109
00:07:10,466 --> 00:07:15,713
Basically, I was in Houston
working at the Johnson Space Center,

110
00:07:15,714 --> 00:07:19,203
becoming more experienced in operations.

111
00:07:19,763 --> 00:07:23,879
I was a good scientist. I had a PhD 
from Cambridge in Astrophysics,

112
00:07:24,149 --> 00:07:28,816
but I had to show
to the astronaut colleagues

113
00:07:28,817 --> 00:07:30,616
that I would be working with

114
00:07:30,617 --> 00:07:32,846
--many of whom had
military backgrounds,

115
00:07:32,847 --> 00:07:35,574
and could fly fast fighter jets,
for example,

116
00:07:35,575 --> 00:07:39,024
or could work
as special operations engineers--

117
00:07:39,025 --> 00:07:40,269
I had to show them

118
00:07:40,270 --> 00:07:42,607
that I could actually think well,

119
00:07:43,334 --> 00:07:46,736
on a timeline, using procedures,

120
00:07:46,737 --> 00:07:48,551
not panic, not freeze up,

121
00:07:48,853 --> 00:07:51,912
and be reliable
in carrying out operations

122
00:07:51,913 --> 00:07:53,998
that were basically irreversible.

123
00:07:53,999 --> 00:07:57,883
When you fire a solid rocket motor,
that's irreversible; you can't undo it,

124
00:07:57,884 --> 00:08:01,472
so you must do it at the right time,
and in the right direction.

125
00:08:01,473 --> 00:08:04,310
So that was what I was doing
as a payload officer:

126
00:08:04,311 --> 00:08:06,704
I was building up my resume
to become an astronaut.

127
00:08:09,386 --> 00:08:12,500
There were 
two astronaut selection periods

128
00:08:12,501 --> 00:08:15,625
before I was finally selected.

129
00:08:15,626 --> 00:08:18,875
In each of those I was interviewed,
but I was not good enough

130
00:08:18,876 --> 00:08:24,091
to make the final 20 or so,
15 or so astronauts

131
00:08:24,092 --> 00:08:26,026
that were selected.

132
00:08:26,027 --> 00:08:29,198
When I was 30 years old
it was 1987.

133
00:08:30,727 --> 00:08:39,135
The Space Shuttle Challenger
blew up at the beginning of 1986.

134
00:08:39,630 --> 00:08:42,957
It was a huge trauma for the United States
and maybe for the world,

135
00:08:42,958 --> 00:08:45,875
because so many small children
were watching that launch

136
00:08:45,876 --> 00:08:48,835
because the first teacher,
Christa McAuliffe was flying on it.

137
00:08:50,195 --> 00:08:52,434
Nonetheless, in spite of that accident,

138
00:08:52,435 --> 00:08:55,846
NASA regrouped, found out
what the problem was,

139
00:08:56,490 --> 00:09:00,447
and corrected it, and during that time
it needed to select more astronauts,

140
00:09:00,448 --> 00:09:03,319
not just because astronauts had left
because of the accident

141
00:09:03,439 --> 00:09:05,953
but because time had passed.

142
00:09:05,954 --> 00:09:12,910
I was interviewed the third time in 1987

143
00:09:12,911 --> 00:09:15,645
and selected in August of that year

144
00:09:15,646 --> 00:09:18,831
and from that point onwards,
I had a career at NASA

145
00:09:18,832 --> 00:09:23,963
from 1987 until 2013
as a NASA astronaut.

146
00:09:30,125 --> 00:09:34,250
OK, GNC, Guidance Navigation and Control

147
00:09:35,109 --> 00:09:39,024
is the moniker by which,
at least in the Western world,

148
00:09:39,672 --> 00:09:42,833
we describe the spacecraft systems

149
00:09:42,834 --> 00:09:48,293
that are required to guide, i.e., control

150
00:09:49,292 --> 00:09:53,434
a spacecraft in a specific direction
and at a specific speed.

151
00:09:54,719 --> 00:09:56,525
That's the guidance part.

152
00:09:56,881 --> 00:10:00,477
Navigation is the means
by which as you do that,

153
00:10:00,478 --> 00:10:04,438
the spacecraft looks around
with its sensors

154
00:10:04,439 --> 00:10:08,363
and knows where it is at this moment

155
00:10:09,011 --> 00:10:14,000
and knows where it needs to go
later on, where it's trying to get to,

156
00:10:14,001 --> 00:10:16,063
for example, geosynchronous orbit,

157
00:10:16,064 --> 00:10:18,636
and that navigation is done with sensors;

158
00:10:18,637 --> 00:10:23,721
and then control is the method
by which you actually move the spacecraft

159
00:10:24,466 --> 00:10:30,319
to achieve the convergence of the guidance
which is where we want to be;

160
00:10:30,478 --> 00:10:32,763
the navigation is where we are,

161
00:10:32,764 --> 00:10:35,936
and the control, it moves
rocket motors or thrusters

162
00:10:36,579 --> 00:10:43,067
to make the other two come together,
the guidance and the navigation.

163
00:10:43,520 --> 00:10:48,515
We use the word "converge"
in the space business.

164
00:10:51,669 --> 00:10:55,870
In the Space Shuttle 
there are a number of sensors,

165
00:10:55,871 --> 00:10:58,114
and I start with the sensors first

166
00:10:58,115 --> 00:11:03,207
before we go on to the guidance,
briefly, and then the control.

167
00:11:03,846 --> 00:11:08,846
The sensors on the Space Shuttle
for knowing where it is, are many.

168
00:11:09,579 --> 00:11:14,291
There are 
three inertial measurement units.

169
00:11:14,736 --> 00:11:16,364
These basically consist

170
00:11:16,364 --> 00:11:22,198
of three individual gyroscopes and gimbals

171
00:11:23,429 --> 00:11:27,419
that originally were made
as mechanical gyroscopes,

172
00:11:27,419 --> 00:11:31,072
but were then subsequently replaced
with laser gyroscopes.

173
00:11:31,973 --> 00:11:35,788
Those inertial measurement units
are able to detect

174
00:11:35,789 --> 00:11:39,750
absolute orientation of the Space Shuttle

175
00:11:39,751 --> 00:11:42,710
or of the box, the platform, the IMU,

176
00:11:42,714 --> 00:11:44,619
relative to the stars.

177
00:11:45,001 --> 00:11:50,203
And they have to be aligned
to a specific set of stars

178
00:11:50,204 --> 00:11:52,931
before you begin any navigation task.

179
00:11:53,490 --> 00:11:56,584
With the Space Shuttle,
that began on the launch pad,

180
00:11:56,585 --> 00:12:00,467
and the tail of the Space Shuttle
was pointed to due south.

181
00:12:01,760 --> 00:12:05,479
They would align
the inertial measurement units

182
00:12:05,480 --> 00:12:07,941
on the launchpad before liftoff.

183
00:12:09,616 --> 00:12:11,353
That was one set of equipment,

184
00:12:11,354 --> 00:12:13,555
and they are the key
by which the Space Shuttle

185
00:12:13,675 --> 00:12:16,231
knows which way it's pointing.

186
00:12:16,583 --> 00:12:22,356
Next, in space, there's
another set of measurement units

187
00:12:22,357 --> 00:12:25,860
that measure angular rates,
not just the angle that you are

188
00:12:25,861 --> 00:12:29,761
in terms of absolute space,
inertial space

189
00:12:29,762 --> 00:12:33,473
but the rate 
at which the angles are changing.

190
00:12:33,884 --> 00:12:35,777
They are called <i>rate gyros</i>

191
00:12:35,778 --> 00:12:39,431
and there were, I think, a set
of four of those on the Space Shuttle;

192
00:12:39,432 --> 00:12:41,489
some at the back end of the Space Shuttle

193
00:12:41,490 --> 00:12:43,938
and some at the front end
of the Space Shuttle,

194
00:12:43,939 --> 00:12:48,862
because the Space Shuttle
was of the order of 50 meters long

195
00:12:48,863 --> 00:12:53,273
and for that reason,
rates at one end of the vehicle

196
00:12:53,274 --> 00:12:55,402
might be different
from rates at the other

197
00:12:55,417 --> 00:12:58,792
due to flection
of the whole spacecraft structure.

198
00:12:58,793 --> 00:13:00,884
So, you have rate gyros as well.

199
00:13:03,119 --> 00:13:07,817
Once you're in orbit,
those inertial measurement units drift,

200
00:13:07,818 --> 00:13:13,828
and they have more and more error
relative to the inertial reference frame

201
00:13:13,829 --> 00:13:16,120
that they were aligned
to on the launch pad.

202
00:13:16,728 --> 00:13:21,877
The way that they achieve realignment
of the inertial measurement units

203
00:13:21,878 --> 00:13:26,625
is to use two instruments
called star trackers

204
00:13:26,626 --> 00:13:33,082
and one looked out the <i>+Y</i> axis
of the Space Shuttle,

205
00:13:33,083 --> 00:13:38,500
and the other looked up
the <i>-Z</i> axis of the Space Shuttle.

206
00:13:40,633 --> 00:13:44,797
Those are the sensors
on the Space Shuttle for navigation.

207
00:13:46,785 --> 00:13:49,876
Control: so how do you control this?

208
00:13:50,116 --> 00:13:53,137
That's a fairly obvious one
when you look at the Space Shuttle.

209
00:13:53,138 --> 00:13:57,486
The Space Shuttle is basically
a combination of aircraft and rocket.

210
00:13:58,149 --> 00:13:59,910
Let's talk about the rocket bit.

211
00:13:59,911 --> 00:14:04,205
The rocket control starts
with the three main engine bells

212
00:14:04,206 --> 00:14:09,853
that burn cryogenic oxygen and hydrogen
at the bottom of the shuttle,

213
00:14:09,854 --> 00:14:12,790
and they can vector in two planes,

214
00:14:14,448 --> 00:14:16,861
and you call that thrust vector control

215
00:14:16,862 --> 00:14:21,374
of each individual engine nozzle,
or engine bell.

216
00:14:21,375 --> 00:14:23,542
You can see them
like a bell, like a <i>cupula</i>.

217
00:14:24,542 --> 00:14:30,751
The solid rocket boosters also could
gimbal their nozzles in two planes,

218
00:14:32,216 --> 00:14:36,329
and with a combination of the two
solid rocket boosters on either side

219
00:14:36,334 --> 00:14:38,501
gimbaling their thrust back to control

220
00:14:38,504 --> 00:14:40,555
as well as the three main engines,

221
00:14:40,989 --> 00:14:44,215
you can control the attitude
of the Space Shuttle

222
00:14:44,216 --> 00:14:49,127
in all three directions:
pitch, roll, and yaw during launch.

223
00:14:51,073 --> 00:14:56,088
In addition, once the solid rocket
boosters have come off,

224
00:14:56,089 --> 00:14:59,373
and once the main engines
of the Space Shuttle

225
00:14:59,374 --> 00:15:03,751
have ceased operating
and you're in space, in orbit,

226
00:15:05,231 --> 00:15:08,721
then there are two additional systems

227
00:15:08,722 --> 00:15:11,830
that can be used
to control the spacecraft.

228
00:15:12,981 --> 00:15:18,652
One of them are two larger engine bells

229
00:15:19,403 --> 00:15:23,302
than the reaction control system,
which are small, little rocket motors.

230
00:15:23,951 --> 00:15:27,014
The larger engine bells
that are on the back of the Space Shuttle

231
00:15:27,134 --> 00:15:29,356
called the <i>Orbital Maneuvering System</i>.

232
00:15:29,375 --> 00:15:33,672
They used hydrazine
and nitrogen tetroxide propellants

233
00:15:33,673 --> 00:15:39,300
to fire briefly to change the orbit
of the Space Shuttle up or down

234
00:15:39,301 --> 00:15:42,126
in apogee and perigee,

235
00:15:42,127 --> 00:15:47,373
and also, most importantly, to provide
the impulse to deal with the Space Shuttle

236
00:15:47,374 --> 00:15:52,145
to bring it back into the atmosphere
so that it can return to our landing site.

237
00:15:53,209 --> 00:15:55,811
Those are called
the <i>OMS Maneuvering System</i>.

238
00:15:55,812 --> 00:15:58,751
They also gimballed in two planes each.

239
00:16:00,097 --> 00:16:05,272
Then the fine control--
and this is the way most satellites work,

240
