00:31:39,976 --> 00:31:41,702
and that's what the Russians used.

478
00:31:41,702 --> 00:31:46,426
They adapted a modem for radio hams
to send text files out.

479
00:31:46,987 --> 00:31:50,210
I would get these text files
that were written in Russian

480
00:31:50,211 --> 00:31:53,598
on a DOS operating system laptop,

481
00:31:53,599 --> 00:31:57,583
and then I would print them out
and give them to the crew members,

482
00:31:57,584 --> 00:31:58,984
Vasily and Sasha,

483
00:31:58,984 --> 00:32:03,157
and they would then read them and say,
"These are our instructions for the day."

484
00:32:03,158 --> 00:32:05,502
At the same time,
I got my instructions that way,

485
00:32:05,503 --> 00:32:11,220
but my role in that crew was to act
as the communications officer,

486
00:32:11,221 --> 00:32:13,006
getting the mail.

487
00:32:13,709 --> 00:32:16,657
Then I'd read my mail and it would say,

488
00:32:16,667 --> 00:32:21,917
"Go and operate the SVET greenhouse."

489
00:32:22,264 --> 00:32:24,670
This was a greenhouse that grew plants,

490
00:32:24,671 --> 00:32:28,533
and I had to put the seeds
into the seed trays,

491
00:32:28,534 --> 00:32:32,677
make sure that they didn't float off
through the fan of the greenhouse

492
00:32:32,678 --> 00:32:38,512
and grow plants that looked
a bit like the vegetable broccoli.

493
00:32:38,513 --> 00:32:40,135
In fact, they would flower,

494
00:32:40,135 --> 00:32:42,887
and I would have to collect
the pollen with bee sticks

495
00:32:42,887 --> 00:32:44,547
and then take the pollen

496
00:32:44,547 --> 00:32:49,103
and fertilize the flowers

497
00:32:49,103 --> 00:32:52,663
with those bee sticks

498
00:32:52,663 --> 00:32:55,792
so that they would then produce seed
and produce another generation of seed,

499
00:32:55,792 --> 00:32:57,538
so that was an interesting experiment.

500
00:32:57,539 --> 00:33:02,489
I had an experiment then
that I would go off with beetles in it,

501
00:33:02,490 --> 00:33:04,490
and it was a beetle experiment.

502
00:33:04,491 --> 00:33:08,935
These beetles were great, big things,
about this size, that came from Kazakhstan

503
00:33:08,936 --> 00:33:10,933
and they had a circadian rhythm

504
00:33:10,934 --> 00:33:16,881
that seemed to stay locked in step
with Kazakhstan's local time of day

505
00:33:16,882 --> 00:33:20,910
even though they were in space,
in orbit around the Earth

506
00:33:20,911 --> 00:33:23,194
and going around the Earth
every 90 minutes.

507
00:33:23,195 --> 00:33:24,936
Amazing creatures.

508
00:33:26,138 --> 00:33:29,722
Then, in the evening,
amongst those activities,

509
00:33:29,723 --> 00:33:31,949
we had to do exercise.

510
00:33:31,949 --> 00:33:33,749
There were two treadmills on the Mir,

511
00:33:35,859 --> 00:33:37,850
and rubber bungees as well.

512
00:33:38,469 --> 00:33:42,476
All of us, the whole crew 
were expected to exercise

513
00:33:42,476 --> 00:33:47,004
for about an hour each session
up to twice a day.

514
00:33:47,005 --> 00:33:49,446
When you exercise in space,
you've got all this sweat,

515
00:33:49,566 --> 00:33:52,137
and it pours bubbles on you,

516
00:33:52,138 --> 00:33:55,147
so you have to get cleaned up
from all that sweat.

517
00:33:55,148 --> 00:33:57,272
It doesn't run off,

518
00:33:57,273 --> 00:34:00,522
and that takes another hour
or so to clean up.

519
00:34:00,523 --> 00:34:05,291
So, exercise could take
up to three hours out of the work day,

520
00:34:05,292 --> 00:34:09,022
leaving you about the five or six
for the experiments that you're tending.

521
00:34:16,135 --> 00:34:18,766
The big difference between
the Space Shuttle and the Mir

522
00:34:18,887 --> 00:34:21,998
was that the Space Shuttle was like

523
00:34:22,000 --> 00:34:27,918
a very well scripted,
choreographed mission

524
00:34:28,632 --> 00:34:32,802
where you know pretty much every day
what you have to do,

525
00:34:32,803 --> 00:34:36,440
and you have very specific sequences,
all of which you practiced,

526
00:34:37,246 --> 00:34:41,284
because the Space Shuttle mission
just doesn't go on longer than ten days,

527
00:34:41,985 --> 00:34:44,676
because it can't stay up
longer than that on its own.

528
00:34:44,677 --> 00:34:48,538
On the Mir, or on
the International Space Station,

529
00:34:48,539 --> 00:34:54,196
the experiments have results,
and what you do

530
00:34:54,197 --> 00:34:56,878
based on the experiment result
may be different.

531
00:34:57,846 --> 00:35:00,101
So, you don't train
for all of those results,

532
00:35:00,102 --> 00:35:02,167
and sometimes there'll be a pause,

533
00:35:02,168 --> 00:35:04,917
and the investigators who are responsible

534
00:35:04,918 --> 00:35:07,460
and who own those experiments
on the ground will say,

535
00:35:07,461 --> 00:35:11,905
"Michael, we're not going to have you
work on the greenhouse today.

536
00:35:12,419 --> 00:35:17,219
We're going to have you work
with growing colloids in space."

537
00:35:17,834 --> 00:35:19,460
And you go, "OK."

538
00:35:19,474 --> 00:35:25,552
It's very flexible, much more like coming
to the office, coming to the laboratory

539
00:35:25,553 --> 00:35:31,207
type of job where you didn't really know
what was coming up the next week

540
00:35:31,208 --> 00:35:33,861
because it depended,
really, on the priorities

541
00:35:33,862 --> 00:35:36,431
of what was going on
this week on the station.

542
00:35:36,432 --> 00:35:41,098
Then, of course, the equipment breaks
or cargo ships arrive,

543
00:35:41,099 --> 00:35:46,242
or emergencies happen
that can change your day.

544
00:35:46,265 --> 00:35:49,065
And so that's the difference in character

545
00:35:49,066 --> 00:35:52,115
between a space station,
a long duration mission,

546
00:35:52,116 --> 00:35:56,762
and a short, directed, focused
Space Shuttle mission.

547
00:36:02,971 --> 00:36:06,349
On the Mir space station, 
this was the very first interaction

548
00:36:06,350 --> 00:36:10,964
of American astronauts
with Russian cosmonauts

549
00:36:10,965 --> 00:36:17,464
since the Apollo-Soyuz
joint docking program

550
00:36:17,464 --> 00:36:19,278
in 1975,

551
00:36:19,278 --> 00:36:22,091
which is when I was still
in university-- actually, school.

552
00:36:23,987 --> 00:36:29,116
This is a big deal
for Americans and Russians.

553
00:36:29,117 --> 00:36:31,031
It was the end of the Cold War,

554
00:36:31,032 --> 00:36:33,837
and it was a way 
by which Americans and Russians

555
00:36:33,838 --> 00:36:36,826
could show they were working
together in space.

556
00:36:36,905 --> 00:36:42,502
Nonetheless, that meant the Russians
had had no experience speaking English,

557
00:36:42,503 --> 00:36:45,646
and it meant that Americans,
including Michael Foale,

558
00:36:45,647 --> 00:36:48,604
had no experience speaking Russian.

559
00:36:48,605 --> 00:36:51,510
The biggest challenge for me

560
00:36:52,456 --> 00:36:56,240
and the other American astronauts
who were sent to Mir

561
00:36:56,241 --> 00:36:58,200
was to learn the Russian language,

562
00:36:58,201 --> 00:37:00,034
because the Mir was already built.

563
00:37:00,035 --> 00:37:05,587
There were no labels on the equipment
in Russian and English

564
00:37:05,588 --> 00:37:08,042
like there are on
the International Space Station.

565
00:37:08,441 --> 00:37:11,122
On Mir, they were all in Russian,

566
00:37:11,123 --> 00:37:13,437
so all of us had to learn Russian.

567
00:37:13,438 --> 00:37:15,879
We went through intensive
Russian language training.

568
00:37:16,226 --> 00:37:21,196
It took, probably, three months
of dedicated eight hours a day,

569
00:37:21,197 --> 00:37:24,053
one on one Russian language training,

570
00:37:24,054 --> 00:37:28,406
before the Russians in Star City,
where I was living with my family,

571
00:37:28,407 --> 00:37:31,513
said we are ready now
to have lectures in Russian.

572
00:37:31,910 --> 00:37:36,899
So because of that extra training
that I received in learning Russian,

573
00:37:36,900 --> 00:37:39,989
Russian cosmonauts didn't have
any extra training

574
00:37:39,989 --> 00:37:41,641
to learn English at that point.

575
00:37:41,641 --> 00:37:44,443
They do now, going to 
the International Space Station.

576
00:37:45,088 --> 00:37:50,616
So when I meet cosmonauts
today in America, in Houston,

577
00:37:50,617 --> 00:37:53,680
and they're young cosmonauts
and they're trying to learn English,

578
00:37:53,681 --> 00:37:57,443
I know I can talk to them in Russian,
but I don't; I let them speak English

579
00:37:57,444 --> 00:38:00,460
because I remember what Sasha said to me.

580
00:38:06,391 --> 00:38:11,339
All of the communications on the Mir
went through Moscow, in general.

581
00:38:11,992 --> 00:38:15,268
For emergencies, there were
two ground stations

582
00:38:15,269 --> 00:38:17,908
set up in the United States

583
00:38:17,909 --> 00:38:22,513
that would allow us to talk
to Americans, basically,

584
00:38:22,514 --> 00:38:24,542
for about ten minutes.

585
00:38:24,543 --> 00:38:26,596
They were sometimes scheduled,

586
00:38:26,597 --> 00:38:30,513
but most of the time, all of it
went through ground stations

587
00:38:30,514 --> 00:38:33,701
over the Russian territories,

588
00:38:34,213 --> 00:38:38,014
and were funneled up through Moscow

589
00:38:38,015 --> 00:38:41,298
and we called it "Glavnyi Operator",

590
00:38:41,299 --> 00:38:42,960
which is like a CAPCOM.

591
00:38:59,232 --> 00:39:04,067
The collision of the cargo spacecraft
took place about six weeks

592
00:39:04,068 --> 00:39:10,848
into this four and a half month
stay of mine on the Space Station MIR,

593
00:39:11,908 --> 00:39:16,069
and the reasons for it
are a different story,

594
00:39:16,070 --> 00:39:22,439
but the result was
that it hit the Space Station Mir

595
00:39:22,440 --> 00:39:25,648
so that it actually went out of attitude.

596
00:39:25,649 --> 00:39:31,360
In fact, it was out of attitude
for normal solar power collection

597
00:39:31,361 --> 00:39:38,119
to enable the docking of the cargo ship
in a proper direction.

598
00:39:41,351 --> 00:39:46,121
Once the collision had taken place,
the Space Station tumbled,

599
00:39:46,122 --> 00:39:49,182
and as it tumbles, as it moves,

600
00:39:49,183 --> 00:39:51,624
its solar arrays no longer
point towards the Sun

601
00:39:51,625 --> 00:39:55,196
so if the Sun's over
here and it's tumbling,

602
00:39:55,197 --> 00:39:58,035
the solar array can't see the Sun anymore,

603
00:39:58,036 --> 00:40:03,981
and the electric power of the station
basically went to zero,

604
00:40:03,982 --> 00:40:06,400
and all we were left with
were the batteries.

605
00:40:06,401 --> 00:40:09,261
Well, the batteries there only had

606
00:40:09,262 --> 00:40:14,157
enough capacity for about
one and a half orbits,

607
00:40:14,158 --> 00:40:17,073
about two hours, and then you're done.

608
00:40:17,074 --> 00:40:19,351
You've got no more power on the station.

609
00:40:19,352 --> 00:40:22,267
So the immediate consequence
of the collision

610
00:40:22,268 --> 00:40:27,733
was that we'd lost all electrical power.

611
00:40:27,734 --> 00:40:31,041
All of the fans, I mean,
to you as an astronaut

612
00:40:31,042 --> 00:40:32,668
or a cosmonaut onboard,

613
00:40:32,705 --> 00:40:35,059
the first thing you notice
is the lights go off.

614
00:40:35,060 --> 00:40:36,424
(laughter)

615
00:40:36,425 --> 00:40:38,132
And you also notice something,

616
00:40:38,133 --> 00:40:41,051
the set, it becomes really, really quiet,

617
00:40:41,489 --> 00:40:43,553
and that's because all of the fans,

618
00:40:43,554 --> 00:40:45,976
and there are fans
everywhere on the spacecraft

619
00:40:45,977 --> 00:40:51,309
moving air around so that carbon dioxide
doesn't accumulate and suffocate you,

620
00:40:51,310 --> 00:40:53,942
and also brings fresh oxygen
so that you can breathe it.

621
00:40:54,370 --> 00:40:56,884
Those fans that are always
humming and whirring,

622
00:40:56,885 --> 00:41:00,154
they're just like computer fans
if you've listened to your computer.

623
00:41:00,155 --> 00:41:02,501
They all went and stopped,

624
00:41:02,502 --> 00:41:06,207
so it was absolutely silent, and dark.

625
00:41:07,054 --> 00:41:09,773
Then, as we go around the Earth
every 90 minutes

626
00:41:09,774 --> 00:41:15,037
and the dark-- the night pass
can be about 30 minutes long,

627
00:41:16,100 --> 00:41:18,416
you go into the dark side of the Earth,

628
00:41:18,417 --> 00:41:23,291
and it starts to get cold
because there's no heat

629
00:41:23,292 --> 00:41:28,001
and the temperature of space
around the Earth is about -150º C,

630
00:41:28,912 --> 00:41:32,471
so the space station
is getting really, really cold.

631
00:41:32,472 --> 00:41:35,005
So it's cold, quiet, and dark.

632
00:41:35,006 --> 00:41:37,184
That's the consequence
to you as an astronaut.

633
00:41:37,500 --> 00:41:40,859
From a recovery point of view,

634
00:41:40,860 --> 00:41:44,760
our task was to try
and get electrical power

635
00:41:44,761 --> 00:41:46,797
and of course, 
we can't talk to the ground,

636
00:41:46,798 --> 00:41:48,513
and the ground can't talk to us,

637
00:41:48,514 --> 00:41:50,237
because there's no electrical power.

638
00:41:50,918 --> 00:41:52,525
So our task was,

639
00:41:52,525 --> 00:41:57,655
and this is what Sasha, and myself,
and Vasily Tsibliyev did,

640
00:41:57,655 --> 00:41:59,377
Sasha Lazutkin I mentioned;

641
00:42:00,580 --> 00:42:07,034
we came up with a scheme to do something
that had never been done

642
00:42:07,035 --> 00:42:11,171
before with the Mir station
in that configuration,

643
00:42:11,923 --> 00:42:16,515
which was to try and disconnect
the electrical power

644
00:42:16,516 --> 00:42:22,106
of the Soyuz lifeboat spacecraft
from the Mir space station,

645
00:42:22,107 --> 00:42:24,978
disconnect its power,
so that we could turn its batteries on.

646
00:42:26,235 --> 00:42:29,772
That took about two orbits,
about three hours

647
00:42:29,773 --> 00:42:30,873
(laughter)

648
00:42:30,874 --> 00:42:37,738
and once we got that achieved,
we then turned the Soyuz spacecraft on,

649
00:42:38,417 --> 00:42:40,069
using its batteries.

650
00:42:40,948 --> 00:42:44,846
And fire and disconnect its guidance,
navigation, and control system,

651
00:42:45,625 --> 00:42:47,867
which thought, "Hey, I'm a little Soyuz.

652
00:42:47,868 --> 00:42:51,156
"I'm nimble and I expect 
that when I fire my thruster this way,

653
00:42:51,157 --> 00:42:53,018
I'll get this much angular rate."

654
00:42:53,019 --> 00:42:55,526
All this had to be
disconnected in the Soyuz

655
00:42:55,527 --> 00:43:00,680
because we had the Mir space station
which weighs 100 tons attached to it,

656
00:43:00,681 --> 00:43:04,057
but the goal was to use the Soyuz
to move the space station

657
00:43:04,058 --> 00:43:08,695
in attitude about two axes;
we couldn't control about the roll axis

658
00:43:08,696 --> 00:43:11,111
because the moment was just too small.

659
00:43:11,112 --> 00:43:14,511
But about pitch and yaw of the Soyuz,

660
00:43:14,512 --> 00:43:17,127
we were going to try and move the station

661
00:43:17,128 --> 00:43:19,698
to have a spin so that its solar arrays

662
00:43:19,699 --> 00:43:22,916
pointed towards the Sun as we rotated

663
00:43:22,917 --> 00:43:25,732
in a fairly stable orientation.

664
00:43:25,733 --> 00:43:27,954
As it turned out, that moment of inertia,

665
00:43:27,955 --> 00:43:30,130
that axis we were trying to spin about

666
00:43:30,131 --> 00:43:36,376
is the middle moment of inertia
of an irregular body

667
00:43:36,377 --> 00:43:44,780
and anyone who's studied
mechanics and kinematics at a high level

668
00:43:44,781 --> 00:43:48,220
will know that the middle moment
of inertia is unstable,

669
00:43:48,221 --> 00:43:50,700
and I suspected that at the time,
but we didn't know

670
00:43:50,701 --> 00:43:54,403
what the moments of inertia
were of the Mir station about those axes.

671
00:43:54,404 --> 00:43:59,878
What that meant was that we would spin
for about two orbits one way,

672
00:43:59,879 --> 00:44:02,477
basically getting some sunlight,

673
00:44:02,478 --> 00:44:05,254
and we were able to turn
the lights on and the fans were on,

674
00:44:05,255 --> 00:44:07,122
and we were able to talk to the ground,

675
00:44:07,242 --> 00:44:10,017
but then, after two orbits,
it would do a kind of a flip,

676
00:44:10,272 --> 00:44:15,552
and then it would face the other way
and <i>not</i> get any sunlight.

677
00:44:16,245 --> 00:44:19,643
And we'd go another two orbits
without any sunlight on the solar arrays,

678
00:44:19,644 --> 00:44:21,734
and then it would be to do another flip,

679
00:44:21,735 --> 00:44:24,411
and then we would get
sunlight on the arrays again.

680
00:44:25,890 --> 00:44:29,249
Then, by getting the batteries charged up,

681
00:44:29,450 --> 00:44:35,595
then we were able to talk to Moscow
over the Russian territory,

682
00:44:35,596 --> 00:44:37,252
over their ground sites,

683
00:44:37,253 --> 00:44:41,821
and the Russian Mir operators in Moscow

684
00:44:41,822 --> 00:44:46,972
were able to send commands
to activate the thrusters,

685
00:44:46,973 --> 00:44:50,175
the reaction control system thrusters
of the Mir station

686
00:44:50,176 --> 00:44:53,314
to actually stop the spin
that we put on it,

687
00:44:53,315 --> 00:44:58,531
and to then, slowly and methodically,

688
00:44:58,532 --> 00:45:03,508
get the solar arrays stable, pointed
and not spinning towards the Sun

689
00:45:03,509 --> 00:45:07,488
and from that point on, we were
basically in a recovered situation.

690
00:45:07,489 --> 00:45:09,683
However, the consequence of the collision

691
00:45:11,230 --> 00:45:15,390
was that it created a hole
in the station at that moment,

692
00:45:15,929 --> 00:45:19,469
and Sasha and I, over a period
of about six minutes,

693
00:45:19,470 --> 00:45:24,172
had to disconnect large electrical cables

694
00:45:24,173 --> 00:45:27,527
going to that module
that had been punctured.

695
00:45:27,528 --> 00:45:29,885
It was called the Spektr module,

696
00:45:29,886 --> 00:45:32,508
and as we're disconnecting those cables,

697
00:45:32,509 --> 00:45:36,895
we disconnected 30%
of the electrical power of the Mir

698
00:45:37,455 --> 00:45:40,287
so that power wasn't available at all,

699
00:45:40,288 --> 00:45:43,540
and as a result of that power cut,

700
00:45:43,541 --> 00:45:50,711
two of the other modules had to be
completely left powered off

701
00:45:50,712 --> 00:45:55,428
and were cold and collecting
a lot of water as condensation,

702
00:45:55,429 --> 00:45:57,531
maybe two or three tons of water.

703
00:45:57,532 --> 00:46:02,172
Two or three cubic meters of water
were collecting in those modules

704
00:46:02,173 --> 00:46:07,987
as we lived and made do
with the base block of the Mir station.

705
00:46:13,751 --> 00:46:19,465
Lazutkin and I had to disconnect
the Spektr solar power arrays

706
00:46:19,466 --> 00:46:22,476
so that we could put
a patch cover in place

707
00:46:22,477 --> 00:46:25,695
and stop the air leaving the space station
through that module.

708
00:46:27,156 --> 00:46:31,630
About three weeks later,

709
00:46:31,631 --> 00:46:34,544
another cargo ship was sent to us

710
00:46:34,623 --> 00:46:38,171
which docked
automatically and successfully,

711
00:46:38,172 --> 00:46:43,765
and it carried with it a plug
with cable pass-through plugs

712
00:46:43,766 --> 00:46:49,778
that allowed another crew 
that was sent up after Sasha and Vasily.

713
00:46:49,778 --> 00:46:51,960
I stayed onboard,

714
00:46:51,961 --> 00:46:55,843
but another Russian crew was sent up,
so I had two crews,

715
00:46:55,844 --> 00:47:00,451
and they performed an <i>inside</i> spacewalk

716
00:47:01,228 --> 00:47:06,315
to connect that hatch plug,
to connect up the cables

717
00:47:06,316 --> 00:47:09,491
that Sasha and I had disconnected
to save the space station.

718
00:47:10,858 --> 00:47:15,252
That was done about
two months after the collision,

719
00:47:15,253 --> 00:47:22,149
and then finally, I went outside
with Anatoly Solovyev, the Commander,

720
00:47:22,150 --> 00:47:26,757
to look for the damage
on the outside of the Spektr module.

721
00:47:27,552 --> 00:47:30,935
We could see the damage,
but we couldn't find the hole,

722
00:47:30,936 --> 00:47:33,489
and that was in September,

723
00:47:33,490 --> 00:47:41,773
and just as the Space Shuttle
was coming to bring me home in October,

724
00:47:41,774 --> 00:47:46,299
I had worked to dry up all of the water

725
00:47:46,300 --> 00:47:49,513
that was in the two modules
that had been powered off,

726
00:47:49,514 --> 00:47:55,692
and we were just preparing
to turn those modules back on,

727
00:47:55,693 --> 00:47:59,892
but that never happened while I was there.

728
00:47:59,893 --> 00:48:02,133
I think it happened after I left.

729
00:48:02,134 --> 00:48:06,124
To answer your question briefly,
about three months, at least.

730
00:48:14,076 --> 00:48:18,239
I wanted to be an astronaut
from the age of six, until, well, now.

731
00:48:18,240 --> 00:48:19,540
(chuckles)

732
00:48:19,541 --> 00:48:23,645
And my father was a Royal Air Force pilot

733
00:48:24,242 --> 00:48:31,585
and I was very impressed 
by the romance, the idea of flying.

734
00:48:32,641 --> 00:48:34,540
I loved watching birds.

735
00:48:34,541 --> 00:48:38,896
I had many, many aircraft models.

736
00:48:38,897 --> 00:48:43,203
When I learned about
the American space program

737
00:48:43,204 --> 00:48:46,912
and the goal of landing on the Moon,

738
00:48:46,913 --> 00:48:49,085
I was about six years old, man!

739
00:48:49,086 --> 00:48:52,406
I sort of told myself
I wanted to be an astronaut.

740
00:48:52,407 --> 00:48:54,788
At some point, I wanted
to cure cancer as well,

741
00:48:54,789 --> 00:48:56,817
because my uncle died of cancer,

742
00:48:56,818 --> 00:48:59,901
but that was my goal.

743
00:48:59,902 --> 00:49:05,804
The way I saw it happening was
to become a pilot in the Royal Air Force

744
00:49:05,805 --> 00:49:07,165
and become a test pilot,

745
00:49:07,165 --> 00:49:09,466
because that's the way 
all the astronauts had done

746
00:49:09,466 --> 00:49:12,341
as far as I knew, up to that point.

747
00:49:12,342 --> 00:49:16,508
But when I applied to the Royal Air Force
for the actual medical tests,

748
00:49:16,509 --> 00:49:19,540
I didn't pass the eye tests.

749
00:49:19,541 --> 00:49:24,956
That meant-- I was devastated by this news

750
00:49:24,957 --> 00:49:27,072
and changed all of my plans.

751
00:49:27,073 --> 00:49:32,897
I was one of the rare boys who had an idea
of what he wanted to do when I grew up

752
00:49:32,898 --> 00:49:37,642
and all of a sudden, I thought I couldn't
do what I wanted to do when I grew up.

753
00:49:37,643 --> 00:49:41,529
However, I was always good
at physics and making model airplanes,

754
00:49:41,530 --> 00:49:44,037
and I basically focused on that,

755
00:49:44,038 --> 00:49:48,963
and worked at the physics,
got to the University of Cambridge,

756
00:49:48,964 --> 00:49:51,793
studied physics at Cambridge,

757
00:49:51,794 --> 00:49:55,750
and when I was just about
to take my final exams

758
00:49:55,751 --> 00:49:58,878
as an undergraduate
in Physics at Cambridge,

759
00:49:58,879 --> 00:50:03,195
thinking I might be a geophysicist,
or a geologist, or something like that,

760
00:50:03,196 --> 00:50:09,398
I learned that the Space Shuttle program
was looking for scientist astronauts,

761
00:50:09,399 --> 00:50:12,437
and so I suddenly
became very, very focused

762
00:50:12,438 --> 00:50:17,608
on getting a really good physics
exam result as an undergraduate

763
00:50:17,609 --> 00:50:20,182
so I could do the PhD in Physics

764
00:50:20,183 --> 00:50:22,274
because I knew I needed the PhD in Physics

765
00:50:22,275 --> 00:50:24,820
to apply to be a scientist astronaut.
